Following are some points in your code that you need to take care of:

- There are no header guards in any header files i.e. circular inclusion of the same file resulting in redefinitions errors.
- The methods names in header and source files are NOT the same.
- The method chaining is being used with methods returninng `void` type.
- In some cases, the functions are declared in the header file but not defined in the source file.

---

**Header Files**

Use the following format in your headers files:

    // Use pragma directive where compilers support this
    #pragma once
    
    // ... code ...

Otherwise, use header guards like this:

    #ifndef MY_HEADER
    #define MY_HEADER
    
    // ... code ...
    
    #endif

**Method Names**

Make sure that the names of methods in the header and source files are the same.

    // Test.hpp
    class Test
    {
    public:
        void print() const;
    };
    
    // Test.cpp
    void Test::print() const
    {
        // ...
    }

**Method Chaining**

The methods have been chained like this:

    complex1-&gt;setReal(real).setImaginary(imag);

But, the methods `setReal()` and `setImaginary()` return nothing i.e. `void`. [Note: setImaginary() doesn&#39;t exist in header. It is `setImag()` but in source file it is defined as `setImaginary()`.]

For chaining, the methods should return the reference of the current object. There are a number of Q&amp;As addressing this on SO!

However, in your current code, you need to do this:

    complex1-&gt;setReal(real);
    complex1-&gt;setImaginary(imag);

---

The above points are just some of the issues that exist in your code. There might be more. You need to follow the errors that your compiler reports and resolve those issues.

In the future, please create an [MCVE][1] to reduce your code so that others may easily follow and reproduce on their own to provide an adequate response.


  [1]: https://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/366988/what-does-mcve-mean

