You can try with [**`Array.prototype.filter()`**][1]

&gt;The `filter()` method creates a new array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function.

[**`Array.prototype.includes()`**][2]

&gt;The `includes()` method determines whether an array includes a certain value among its entries, returning true or false as appropriate.


And [**`Array.prototype.map()`**][3]

&gt;The `map()` method creates a new array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in the calling array.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var jsObjects = [
       {a: 1, b: 2}, 
       {a: 3, b: 4}, 
       {a: 5, b: 6}, 
       {a: 7, b: 8}
    ];

    var myArray = [4,6,8]

    var resArray = jsObjects.filter(i =&gt; myArray.includes(i.b)).map(i =&gt; i.a);
    console.log(resArray);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/filter
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/includes
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map

You can do it using higher order function like `filter, map, find e.t.c`, but as you say you are new to javascript - i think this is the simplest way of understanding and getting the expected result.
&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var jsObjects = [
       {a: 1, b: 2}, 
       {a: 3, b: 4}, 
       {a: 5, b: 6}, 
       {a: 7, b: 8}
    ];

    var myArray = [4,6,8]

    var finalArray = [];

    for(let bValue of myArray) {
      for(let item in jsObjects) {
        if(bValue == jsObjects[item].b) {
          finalArray.push(jsObjects[item].a);
        }
      }
    }

    console.log(finalArray); // [3, 5, 7]

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can use a `new Map()` to store key-value pairs, where `b` is your key and `a` is your value. After that, you can `.map()` your array of `b` values to an array of `a` values using the map you constructed: 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const jsObjects = [
       {a: 1, b: 2}, 
       {a: 3, b: 4}, 
       {a: 5, b: 6}, 
       {a: 7, b: 8}
    ];

    const myArray = [4,6,8];

    const search = new Map(jsObjects.map(({a, b}) =&gt; [b, a]));
    const res = myArray.map(v =&gt; search.get(v));
    console.log(res);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

There are N ways of doing that, none of them without adding a bit of logic.

Even though you are new to JS, I advise you to use HOF like `reduce` ([take a look here to know more about HOF] [1]).

Here&#39;s an example how to do it:

```
const jsObjects = [
  { a: 1, b: 2 },
  { a: 3, b: 4 },
  { a: 5, b: 6 },
  { a: 7, b: 8 }
];

const myArray = [4, 6, 8];
const result = jsObjects.reduce((result, entry) =&gt; {
  if (myArray.includes(entry.b)) {
    result.push(entry.a);

    return result;
  }

  return result;
}, []);

console.log(result) // [3, 5, 7];
```

  [1]: https://medium.com/javascript-scene/higher-order-functions-composing-software-5365cf2cbe99

